{
  "metadata": {
    "name": "Standard Deduction History",
    "description": "Historical federal standard deduction amounts by filing status, including additional deductions for age 65+ and blind taxpayers.",
    "version": "1.2",
    "last_updated": "2026-03-16",
    "sources": [
      "https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-provides-tax-inflation-adjustments-for-tax-year-2026",
      "https://taxfoundation.org/taxedu/glossary/standard-deduction/",
      "IRS Revenue Procedures (annual inflation adjustments)"
    ],
    "notes": [
      "Standard deduction is the baseline deduction for taxpayers who do not itemize.",
      "Age 65+ / blind additional deduction stacks on top of the base amount.",
      "For retirees: standard deduction is critical for calculating taxable income from pensions, SS, and IRA distributions.",
      "TCJA (2018-2025) nearly doubled the standard deduction and eliminated personal exemptions.",
      "2026: If TCJA sunset occurred, personal exemption would return but standard deduction would decrease. Per Rev. Proc. 2025-32, TCJA rates continued."
    ],
    "cross_references": [
      {
        "file": "federal/filing-status-thresholds.json",
        "manifest_key": "filing_status_thresholds",
        "note": "For all 5 filing statuses including MFS and QSS, plus OBBBA senior deduction and blind additional deduction, use filing-status-thresholds. This file provides Single/MFJ/HoH standard deduction history (2001-2026) for trend analysis."
      }
    ]
  },
